{
  "answer": "**The Gaṇapatitattva (slug: unknown-ganapatitattva-66a136) opens with a verse praising Lord Śiva as the interlocutor.** \n\nThis is verse (1), presented in the translation as:  \n\"Gaṇapati questioned Śiva, the giver of success to Gaṅgā and Umā, the son who is teacher to the host of gods, for the glory of the light of power and valor. // (1)\"[^1]\n\nA near-identical phrasing praising Gaṇapati (as Śiva's son) appears later in verse (59) of a mantra:[^2]  \n\"To the son who is teacher to the host of gods, giver of success to Gaṅgā and Umā, for the glory of the light of power and valor, they are victorious, gaining boons and grace. // (59)\"\n\nOther verses reference or invoke Śiva (e.g., perpetual worship in verse 24,[^3] contemplation of Maheśvara in verse 19[^4]), but verse (1) is the work's explicit introductory praise of Lord Śiva.\n\n[^1]: Gaṇapati, *Gaṇapatitattva*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-ganapatitattva-66a136/01/translation/#p-bbfaeb).\n[^2]: Gaṇapati, *Gaṇapatitattva*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-ganapatitattva-66a136/01/translation/#p-ca0b8b).\n[^3]: Gaṇapati, *Gaṇapatitattva*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-ganapatitattva-66a136/01/translation/#p-3619b4).\n[^4]: Gaṇapati, *Gaṇapatitattva*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-ganapatitattva-66a136/01/translation/#p-07043c).",
